    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cheney for Vice President? Some Early Reviews</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Robert W Carr letter, commenting on July 26 article on Gov George Bush's choice of the ultraconservative Dick Cheney as running mate, notes that vice president casts deciding vote when there is tie in Senate</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Bush Names Cheney, Citing 'Integrity' and 'Experience' '' (front page, July 26):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Bush Names Cheney, Citing 'Integrity' and 'Experience' '' (front page, July 26):</p>
        <p>For those who might be tempted to minimize the importance of Dick Cheney's ultraconservative voting record, it may be well to remember that the vice president casts the deciding vote when there is a tie vote in the Senate. This seems especially important because the prospects seem great for a narrow balance between the parties in the Senate as a result of the November election.</p>
        <p>ROBERT W. CARR  Ann Arbor, Mich., July 26, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
